{"title_page": "Supergirl (Stefania song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Supergirl\n| cover      = Stefania - Supergirl.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Stefania Liberakakis|Stefania]]\n| album      =\n| released   = 1 March 2020\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| studio     = Vox Studios\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]]\n| length     = 3:00\n| label      = K2ID\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Dimitris Kontopoulos]]|Arcade|[[Sharon Vaughn]]}}\n| producer   = Arcade (Pavlos Manolis, Anastasios Rammos, Diverno, Gabriel Russell)\n| prev_title = Turn Around\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = \n{{External music video|{{YouTube|83ncXE_fOtI|\"Supergirl\"}}}}\n{{Infobox song contest entry\n| song        = {{flagicon|Greece}} \"Supergirl\"\n| embed = yes\n| year        = 2020\n| country     = Greece\n| artist      = [[Stefania Liberakakis|Stefania]]\n| language    = English\n| composer    = {{hlist|[[Dimitris Kontopoulos]]|Arcade}}\n| lyricist    = {{hlist|[[Dimitris Kontopoulos]]|Arcade|[[Sharon Vaughn]]}}\n| place       = \n| points      = \n| place_semi  = ''Contest cancelled''\n| points_semi = \n| prev        = Better Love\n| prev_link   = Better Love (Katerine Duska song)\n| next        =\n| next_link   =\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Supergirl'''\" (stylized as '''SUPERG!RL''') is a song recorded by Greek-Dutch singer [[Stefania Liberakakis|Stefania]], [[digital download|digitally]] released on 1 March 2020. It was written by [[Dimitris Kontopoulos]], lyricist [[Sharon Vaughn]], and production team Arcade. The song was intended to represent [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020]] before the event's cancellation due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) and its spread throughout the world. Stefania had been internally selected as the country's representative by Greek public broadcaster [[Hellenic Broadcasting Corporation]] (ERT).\n\nMusically the track is a [[dance-pop]] song that encourages teenagers to believe in themselves and pursue their dreams. For promotion, Stefania released a music video of the song and appeared on talk shows in both Greece and the Netherlands.\n\n==Background==\nOn 3 February 2020, during a [[Hellenic Broadcasting Corporation]] (ERT) newscast, Stefania was announced as the Greek entrant for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]] with the song \"Supergirl\".<ref name=\"announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/03/confirmed-stefania-represent-greece-eurovision-2020-supergirl/249074/|title=Confirmed! Stefania will represent Greece at Eurovision 2020 with the song \"SUPERG!RL\"|last=Gallagher|first=Robyn|publisher=Wiwibloggs|accessdate=3 February 2020|date=3 February 2020}}</ref> \"Supergirl\" was written by [[Dimitris Kontopoulos]], lyricist [[Sharon Vaughn]], and production team Arcade, consisting of Anastasios Rammos, Diverno, Gabriel Russell and Pavlos Manolis.<ref name=\"announcement\"/> The song and its accompanying music video were released on 1 March 2020, during ERT's premiere of ''Eurovision Song Contest - Final Countdown'', hosted by Mihalis Marinos.<ref name=\"premiere\">{{Cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/178848/greece-stefania-will-premiere-her-eurovision-entry-supergrl-on-1-march/|title=Greece: Stefania will premiere her Eurovision entry \u2018Superg!rl\u2019 on 1 March|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=17 February 2020|website=EscToday|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> Given that Stefania was the youngest artist ever selected to represent Greece, at 17,<ref name=\"jinek\">{{cite web|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/12/stefania-on-jinek-and-gala-magazine-greece-eurovision-2020/249729/|title=COVER G!RL: Stefania talks Eurovision on Jinek\u2026and gets front page treatment in Gala magazine|last=Jansen|first=Esma|publisher=Wiwibloggs|date=12 February 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> Kontopoulos stated that it was difficult to find the right song for her, as he sought one that would fit both her age and personality.<ref name=\"EBU\"/> The network described the song as an \"up-tempo pop song with ethnic elements\",<ref name=\"EBU\">{{Cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/stefania-to-sing-for-greece-eurovision-2020|title=Here's Stefania's music video for 'SUPERG!RL'|date=1 March 2020|website=Eurovision.tv|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> while Stefania added that it's \"a dance pop song in true [[Ariana Grande]] style\".<ref name=\"premiere\"/> The song encourages teenagers to believe in themselves and pursue their dreams, inspired by Stefania's daily struggles to combine her duties as a student while pursuing her dream of singing.<ref name=\"EBU/><ref name=\"zappit\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.zappit.gr/psychagogia/video/eurovision-2020-afto-einai-to-supergirl-apo-ti-stefania-gia-tin-ellada/2927701|title=Eurovision 2020: \u0391\u03c5\u03c4\u03cc \u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf Supergirl \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7 Stefania \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1|last=|first=|date=1 March 2020|website=Zappit|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 March 2020|language=Greek}}</ref>\n\n==Music video and promotion==\nThe music video was released at the same time as the premiere of the song on 1 March 2020.<ref name=\"premiere\"/> Konstantinos Karydas directed the video, which was filmed at four locations in and around [[Athens]].<ref name=premiere/> Karydas said: {{quote|\"We created a story with surreal elements. We are following a young girl who finds the strength to embrace her specialty in a society that sees her as something foreign. It is a journey of exploration of power within it. The video comes to complement the song, which is dynamic and fresh. The whole team is made up of professionals, who in their field have given 100% to get a perfect result. We also had a great collaboration with Stefania, which surprised us with her hard work and acting skills\".{{efn|Karydas' remarks were in Greek and have been translated.<ref name=\"premiere\"/><ref name=\"zappit\"/>}}}}\nStefania has since been featured in both print and broadcast media in Greece and her native Netherlands. She appeared on the popular Dutch talk show ''Jinek'' speaking of her excitement about participating in the contest and was subsequently featured in a cover shoot for ''[[Gala (magazine)|Gala]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"jinek\"/> The Dutch broadcaster [[VPRO]] was also recording her for a documentary.<ref name=\"jinek\"/> In Greece, Stefania's promotion began a year prior with her performance of the song \"[[Con Calma]]\" at the [[MAD Video Music Awards]] in June 2019.<ref name=\"EBU\"/> In advance of Eurovision, ERT sought to see if Stefania and the Greek audience had a connection.<ref name=\"jinek\"/> Following her selection and appearance on Greek television, she found Greek paparazzi and fans began to recognise her, which Stefania called \"a very funny experience\".<ref name=\"jinek\"/> An unplugged version of the song was performed in late March as part of Kontopoulos' initiative \"Qsessions\" during the COVID-19-related [[Curfews and lockdowns related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|lockdown]]. It served as her first live performance of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/03/31/stefania-sings-supergrl-live-during-dimitris-kontopoulos-unplugged-acoustic-session/252925/|title=Stefania sings \u201cSuperg!rl\u201d live during Dimitris Kontopoulos unplugged acoustic session|last=Adams|first=William Lee|publisher=Wiwibloggs|accessdate=13 April 2020|date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Eurovision Song Contest==\n{{Main|Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020}}\nThe Eurovision Song Contest 2020 was originally scheduled to take place at [[Rotterdam Ahoy]] in [[Rotterdam]], Netherlands and consist of two semi-finals on 12 and 14 May, and a final on 16 May 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020|title=Eurovision Song Contest Rotterdam 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306165402/https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020|archivedate=6 March 2020}}</ref> According to Eurovision rules, each country, except the host nation and the \"[[Eurovision Song Contest#Big Four and Big Five|Big 5]]\" (France, Germany, Italy, Spain and the United Kingdom), would have been required to qualify from one of two semi-finals to compete for the final; the top ten countries from each semi-final would have progressed to the final.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/about/rules|title=Rules \u2013 Eurovision Song Contest|accessdate=31 August 2018|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620160638/https://eurovision.tv/about/rules|archive-date=20 June 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020/first-semi-final/participants|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2020 \u2013 First Semi-Final|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128105055/https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020/first-semi-final/participants|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020/second-semi-final/participants|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2020 \u2013 Second Semi-Final|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128105053/https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020/second-semi-final/participants|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 January 2020, the allocation draw was held, placing \"Supergirl\" into the first half of the second semi-final.<ref name=\"allocation\">{{cite web|last=Groot|first=Evert|title=Which country performs in which Eurovision 2020 Semi-Final|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/host-city-insignia-exchange-semi-final-allocation-draw-2020|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=28 January 2020|date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Fokas Evangelinos was hired to organize the staging and choreography for the performance.<ref name=\"announcement\"/><ref name=\"premiere\"/> However, due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe]], the contest was cancelled on 18 March 2020.<ref name=\"cancel\">{{cite web|title=\u039c\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9\u03ce\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd EBU \u03b7 \u03b4\u03b9\u03b5\u03be\u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03b3\u03ae \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 Eurovision 2020|language=Greek|url=https://press.ert.gr/deltia-typou/mataiothike-apo-tin-ebu-i-diexagogi-tis-eurovision/|website=ert.gr|publisher=[[Hellenic Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=18 March 2020|date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"cancellation\">{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/eurovision-2020-in-rotterdam-is-cancelled|title=Eurovision 2020 in Rotterdam is cancelled|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318140901/https://eurovision.tv/story/eurovision-2020-in-rotterdam-is-cancelled|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The EBU announced soon after that entries intended for 2020 would not be eligible for the following year, though each broadcaster would be able to send either their 2020 representative or a new one.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/intention-to-honour-eurovision-2020-songs-artists|title=Intention to honour Eurovision 2020 songs and artists|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> ERT responded that its intention was to continue its cooperation with Stefania for the next contest in 2021.<ref name=\"cancel\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''Digital download'''{{efn|This acts as a summary of all versions of the single released for digital download.<ref name=\"rel\"/>}}\n#\"Supergirl\" \u2013 3:00\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Country\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| 1 March 2020\n| [[Music download|Digital download]], [[streaming media|streaming]]\n| K2ID\n|{{center|<ref name=\"rel\">Citations regarding the digital release of \"Supergirl\" in various countries:\n*{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gr/album/superg-rl-single/1500416433|title=SUPERG!RL \u2013 Single by Stefania on Apple Music|publisher=[[Apple Music]] (GR)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/superg-rl-single/1500416433|title=SUPERG!RL \u2013 Single by Stefania on Apple Music|publisher=[[Apple Music]] (GB)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/superg-rl-single/1500416433|title=SUPERG!RL \u2013 Single by Stefania on Apple Music|publisher=[[Apple Music]] (US)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/tr/album/superg-rl-single/1500416433|title=SUPERG!RL \u2013 Single by Stefania on Apple Music|publisher=[[Apple Music]] (TR)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of 2020]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of Greece]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Dimitris Kontopoulos]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Supergirl\n| cover      = Stefania - Supergirl.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Stefania Liberakakis|Stefania]]\n| album      =\n| released   = 1 March 2020\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| studio     = Vox Studios\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]]\n| length     = 3:00\n| label      = K2ID\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Dimitris Kontopoulos]]|Arcade|[[Sharon Vaughn]]}}\n| producer   = Arcade (Pavlos Manolis, Anastasios Rammos, Diverno, Gabriel Russell)\n| prev_title = Turn Around\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = \n{{External music video|{{YouTube|83ncXE_fOtI|\"Supergirl\"}}}}\n{{Infobox song contest entry\n| song        = {{flagicon|Greece}} \"Supergirl\"\n| embed = yes\n| year        = 2020\n| country     = Greece\n| artist      = [[Stefania Liberakakis|Stefania]]\n| language    = English\n| composer    = {{hlist|[[Dimitris Kontopoulos]]|Arcade}}\n| lyricist    = {{hlist|[[Dimitris Kontopoulos]]|Arcade|[[Sharon Vaughn]]}}\n| place       = \n| points      = \n| place_semi  = ''Contest cancelled''\n| points_semi = \n| prev        = Better Love\n| prev_link   = Better Love (Katerine Duska song)\n| next        =\n| next_link   =\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Supergirl'''\" (stylized as '''SUPERG!RL''') is a song recorded by Greek-Dutch singer [[Stefania Liberakakis|Stefania]], [[digital download|digitally]] released on 1 March 2020. It was written by [[Dimitris Kontopoulos]], lyricist [[Sharon Vaughn]], and production team Arcade. The song was intended to represent [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020]] before the event's cancellation due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) and its spread throughout the world. Stefania had been internally selected as the country's representative by Greek public broadcaster [[Hellenic Broadcasting Corporation]] (ERT).\n\nMusically the track is a [[dance-pop]] song that encourages teenagers to believe in themselves and pursue their dreams. For promotion, Stefania released a music video of the song and appeared on talk shows in both Greece and the Netherlands.\n\n==Background==\nOn 3 February 2020, during a [[Hellenic Broadcasting Corporation]] (ERT) newscast, Stefania was announced as the Greek entrant for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]] with the song \"Supergirl\".<ref name=\"announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/03/confirmed-stefania-represent-greece-eurovision-2020-supergirl/249074/|title=Confirmed! Stefania will represent Greece at Eurovision 2020 with the song \"SUPERG!RL\"|last=Gallagher|first=Robyn|publisher=Wiwibloggs|accessdate=3 February 2020|date=3 February 2020}}</ref> \"Supergirl\" was written by [[Dimitris Kontopoulos]], lyricist [[Sharon Vaughn]], and production team Arcade, consisting of Anastasios Rammos, Diverno, Gabriel Russell and Pavlos Manolis.<ref name=\"announcement\"/> The song and its accompanying music video were released on 1 March 2020, during ERT's premiere of ''Eurovision Song Contest - Final Countdown'', hosted by Mihalis Marinos.<ref name=\"premiere\">{{Cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/178848/greece-stefania-will-premiere-her-eurovision-entry-supergrl-on-1-march/|title=Greece: Stefania will premiere her Eurovision entry \u2018Superg!rl\u2019 on 1 March|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=17 February 2020|website=EscToday|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> Given that Stefania was the youngest artist ever selected to represent Greece, at 17,<ref name=\"jinek\">{{cite web|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/12/stefania-on-jinek-and-gala-magazine-greece-eurovision-2020/249729/|title=COVER G!RL: Stefania talks Eurovision on Jinek\u2026and gets front page treatment in Gala magazine|last=Jansen|first=Esma|publisher=Wiwibloggs|date=12 February 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> Kontopoulos stated that it was difficult to find the right song for her, as he sought one that would fit both her age and personality.<ref name=\"EBU\"/> The network described the song as an \"up-tempo pop song with ethnic elements\",<ref name=\"EBU\">{{Cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/stefania-to-sing-for-greece-eurovision-2020|title=Here's Stefania's music video for 'SUPERG!RL'|date=1 March 2020|website=Eurovision.tv|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> while Stefania added that it's \"a dance pop song in true [[Ariana Grande]] style\".<ref name=\"premiere\"/> The song encourages teenagers to believe in themselves and pursue their dreams, inspired by Stefania's daily struggles to combine her duties as a student while pursuing her dream of singing.<ref name=\"EBU/><ref name=\"zappit\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.zappit.gr/psychagogia/video/eurovision-2020-afto-einai-to-supergirl-apo-ti-stefania-gia-tin-ellada/2927701|title=Eurovision 2020: \u0391\u03c5\u03c4\u03cc \u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf Supergirl \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7 Stefania \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1|last=|first=|date=1 March 2020|website=Zappit|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 March 2020|language=Greek}}</ref>\n\n==Music video and promotion==\nThe music video was released at the same time as the premiere of the song on 1 March 2020.<ref name=\"premiere\"/> Konstantinos Karydas directed the video, which was filmed at four locations in and around [[Athens]].<ref name=premiere/> Karydas said: {{quote|\"We created a story with surreal elements. We are following a young girl who finds the strength to embrace her specialty in a society that sees her as something foreign. It is a journey of exploration of power within it. The video comes to complement the song, which is dynamic and fresh. The whole team is made up of professionals, who in their field have given 100% to get a perfect result. We also had a great collaboration with Stefania, which surprised us with her hard work and acting skills\".{{efn|Karydas' remarks were in Greek and have been translated.<ref name=\"premiere\"/><ref name=\"zappit\"/>}}}}\nStefania has since been featured in both print and broadcast media in Greece and her native Netherlands. She appeared on the popular Dutch talk show ''Jinek'' speaking of her excitement about participating in the contest and was subsequently featured in a cover shoot for ''[[Gala (magazine)|Gala]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"jinek\"/> The Dutch broadcaster [[VPRO]] was also recording her for a documentary.<ref name=\"jinek\"/> In Greece, Stefania's promotion began a year prior with her performance of the song \"[[Con Calma]]\" at the [[MAD Video Music Awards]] in June 2019.<ref name=\"EBU\"/> In advance of Eurovision, ERT sought to see if Stefania and the Greek audience had a connection.<ref name=\"jinek\"/> Following her selection and appearance on Greek television, she found Greek paparazzi and fans began to recognise her, which Stefania called \"a very funny experience\".<ref name=\"jinek\"/> An unplugged version of the song was performed in late March as part of Kontopoulos' initiative \"Qsessions\" during the COVID-19-related [[Curfews and lockdowns related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|lockdown]]. It served as her first live performance of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/03/31/stefania-sings-supergrl-live-during-dimitris-kontopoulos-unplugged-acoustic-session/252925/|title=Stefania sings \u201cSuperg!rl\u201d live during Dimitris Kontopoulos unplugged acoustic session|last=Adams|first=William Lee|publisher=Wiwibloggs|accessdate=13 April 2020|date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Eurovision Song Contest==\n{{Main|Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020}}\nThe Eurovision Song Contest 2020 was originally scheduled to take place at [[Rotterdam Ahoy]] in [[Rotterdam]], Netherlands and consist of two semi-finals on 12 and 14 May, and a final on 16 May 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020|title=Eurovision Song Contest Rotterdam 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306165402/https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020|archivedate=6 March 2020}}</ref> According to Eurovision rules, each country, except the host nation and the \"[[Eurovision Song Contest#Big Four and Big Five|Big 5]]\" (France, Germany, Italy, Spain and the United Kingdom), would have been required to qualify from one of two semi-finals to compete for the final; the top ten countries from each semi-final would have progressed to the final.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/about/rules|title=Rules \u2013 Eurovision Song Contest|accessdate=31 August 2018|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620160638/https://eurovision.tv/about/rules|archive-date=20 June 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020/first-semi-final/participants|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2020 \u2013 First Semi-Final|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128105055/https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020/first-semi-final/participants|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020/second-semi-final/participants|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2020 \u2013 Second Semi-Final|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128105053/https://eurovision.tv/event/rotterdam-2020/second-semi-final/participants|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 January 2020, the allocation draw was held, placing \"Supergirl\" into the first half of the second semi-final.<ref name=\"allocation\">{{cite web|last=Groot|first=Evert|title=Which country performs in which Eurovision 2020 Semi-Final|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/host-city-insignia-exchange-semi-final-allocation-draw-2020|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=28 January 2020|date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Fokas Evangelinos was hired to organize the staging and choreography for the performance.<ref name=\"announcement\"/><ref name=\"premiere\"/> However, due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe]], the contest was cancelled on 18 March 2020.<ref name=\"cancel\">{{cite web|title=\u039c\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9\u03ce\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd EBU \u03b7 \u03b4\u03b9\u03b5\u03be\u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03b3\u03ae \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 Eurovision 2020|language=Greek|url=https://press.ert.gr/deltia-typou/mataiothike-apo-tin-ebu-i-diexagogi-tis-eurovision/|website=ert.gr|publisher=[[Hellenic Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=18 March 2020|date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"cancellation\">{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/eurovision-2020-in-rotterdam-is-cancelled|title=Eurovision 2020 in Rotterdam is cancelled|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318140901/https://eurovision.tv/story/eurovision-2020-in-rotterdam-is-cancelled|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The EBU announced soon after that entries intended for 2020 would not be eligible for the following year, though each broadcaster would be able to send either their 2020 representative or a new one.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/intention-to-honour-eurovision-2020-songs-artists|title=Intention to honour Eurovision 2020 songs and artists|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> ERT responded that its intention was to continue its cooperation with Stefania for the next contest in 2021.<ref name=\"cancel\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''Digital download'''{{efn|This acts as a summary of all versions of the single released for digital download.<ref name=\"rel\"/>}}\n#\"Supergirl\" \u2013 3:00\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Country\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| 1 March 2020\n| [[Music download|Digital download]], [[streaming media|streaming]]\n| K2ID\n|{{center|<ref name=\"rel\">Citations regarding the digital release of \"Supergirl\" in various countries:\n*{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gr/album/superg-rl-single/1500416433|title=SUPERG!RL \u2013 Single by Stefania on Apple Music|publisher=[[Apple Music]] (GR)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/superg-rl-single/1500416433|title=SUPERG!RL \u2013 Single by Stefania on Apple Music|publisher=[[Apple Music]] (GB)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/superg-rl-single/1500416433|title=SUPERG!RL \u2013 Single by Stefania on Apple Music|publisher=[[Apple Music]] (US)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/tr/album/superg-rl-single/1500416433|title=SUPERG!RL \u2013 Single by Stefania on Apple Music|publisher=[[Apple Music]] (TR)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Eurovision-stub}}\n\n{{Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of 2020]]\n[[Category:Eurovision songs of Greece]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Dimitris Kontopoulos]]\n", "name_user": "Grk1011", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv stub", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supergirl_(Stefania_song)"}
{"title_page": "Neighborhoods in Atlanta", "text_new": "{{about|neighborhoods in the city of Atlanta, Georgia|cities, neighborhoods, and other districts in Greater Atlanta|Atlantakhydgyuhjuh gfd}}\n{{Refimprove|date=August 2017}}\n:{|style=\"background:transparent\"\n|''Note: many unincorporated communities in [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb County]] and [[Cobb County, Georgia]] adjacent to Atlanta, including [[Druid Hills, Georgia|Druid Hills]] [[census-designated place|CDP]] and [[North Druid Hills, Georgia|North Druid Hills]], both in DeKalb County and [[Cumberland, Georgia]] and [[Vinings, Georgia]], both in Cobb County use \"Atlanta\" in their postal address but are not part of the City of Atlanta. See [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb County]] and [[Cobb County, Georgia]]. Also, an unincorporated area in [[Norcross, Georgia]], located in [[Gwinnett County]], uses an Atlanta postal address, while not being a part of the City of Atlanta.''\n|}\n\nThe American city of [[Atlanta, Georgia]] is divided into 242 [[neighborhood]]s officially defined by the city. These \"neighborhoods\" are a mix of traditional neighborhoods; subdivisions or groups of subdivisions; and parts of core areas such as [[Downtown Atlanta|Downtown]] and [[Midtown Atlanta|Midtown]].\n\nThe neighborhoods are divisions of 25 [[neighborhood planning unit]]s or NPUs, which are \"citizen advisory councils that make recommendations to the Mayor and City Council on zoning, land use, and other planning issues\".<ref name=\"NPUs\">{{cite web|title=Neighborhood Planning Unit (NPU)|url=http://www.atlantaga.gov/index.aspx?page=739|website=City of Atlanta|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> There are other non-official but widely recognized named areas within the city, such as [[Intown Atlanta|Intown]], [[West Midtown]], [[Buckhead]], and areas like Northwestern Atlanta identified by compass points.\n\n==Districts==\nThe term \"district\" in Atlanta is generally used for small areas within the official neighborhoods. [[Downtown Atlanta|Downtown]] and [[Midtown Atlanta|Midtown]] Atlanta each contain a number of districts. Another example is [[Little Five Points]], which sits on the border of 3 official neighborhoods.\n\nIn addition, Atlanta has various other divisions such as [[business improvement district]]s, [[Police Patrol Zones of Atlanta|police patrol zones]], and in the unique case of [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]], a \"community\". Most of Atlanta north of the [[I-75]] / [[I-85]] downtown connector is part of the \"Buckhead Community\".\n\n==Areas==\nAlthough all of Atlanta is officially divided into Neighborhood Planning Units, it is more common in the news media<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/atlanta-news/|title=Atlanta News / Georgia News Section|website=ajc|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref> to refer to the larger areas of the city in one of three ways:\n*Downtown, Midtown, and most of the central, east-central, west-central neighborhoods are referred to by their names, as these are well known throughout the Atlanta metro area, and most contain regional \"destinations\", such as the Zoo in Grant Park, or the shops and restaurants in Virginia Highland (other examples include East Lake, East Atlanta, Ormewood, Bankhead, Kirkwood, though they are not limited to these).\n*Buckhead neighborhoods are referred to collectively as Buckhead \u2013 this covers the entire northern fifth of the city (north of the I-75 / I-85 downtown connector)\n*Other areas are generally referred to as part of either \"Northwest\", \"Southwest\", or \"Southeast Atlanta\". However, \"East Atlanta\" refers to a small neighborhood which is part of the 'W' group NPU and does not have the same connotation as the other directional descriptors.\n<!-- Please do NOT include other cities or suburbs, ONLY areas within the city of Atlanta itself. -->\n\n==Neighborhoods (by area)==\nThe city of Atlanta lies in three [[counties in Georgia]]: primarily in [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton]], and partly in [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb]] to the east, and part [[Clayton County, Georgia|Clayton]] south of the county <br />''- Numbers to the right of the neighborhood indicate its position on the map above<br />- \"n\" is a link to the corresponding neighborhood association<br />- \"h\" indicates a link to the homepage of the corresponding historic district (if the neighborhood is one)''\n\n===Intown Atlanta===\nThe term \"intown\" is more commonly used to refer to any neighborhoods within the central part of the city.\n[[File:Neighborhoods of Intown Atlanta.jpg|thumb|900px|left|Neighborhoods of Intown Atlanta]]\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n====Downtown====\n*[[Downtown Atlanta]] [http://www.atlantadna.org n] is a neighborhood that contains the following sub-districts:\n**[[Castleberry Hill]] [http://www.castleberryhill.org n] [http://www.nps.gov/history/Nr/travel/atlanta/cas.htm h]\n**[[Centennial Hill]] district\n**[[Fairlie-Poplar]] district [http://www.nps.gov/history/Nr/travel/atlanta/fai.htm h]\n**[[Five Points (Atlanta)|Five Points]] district\n**[[Hotel District]] [http://www.nps.gov/history/Nr/travel/atlanta/hot.htm h]\n**[[Luckie Marietta]] district\n**[[Peachtree Center]]\n**[[SoNo (Atlanta)|SoNo]] [http://www.sonoatlanta.com n]\n**[[South Downtown]]\n{{col-break}}\n\n====Midtown====\n*[[Midtown Atlanta|Midtown]], as defined by the Midtown Alliance,<ref name=\"Midtown Alliance\">{{cite web|url=http://www.midtownatl.com/life/residential-neighborhoods/midtown-neighborhoods|title=Midtown Alliance|website=Midtownalliance.org|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref> consists of these neighborhoods:\n**The [[Midtown Atlanta|Midtown]]<!-- (7)--> neighborhood proper which contains the districts:\n***Midtown Core\n***Midtown Neighborhood [http://midtownatlanta.org/ n] [[Midtown Historic District (Atlanta, Georgia)|h]]\n**[[Ansley Park]] [http://www.ansleypark.org n]\n**[[Atlantic Station]]<!-- (16)--> [http://www.atlanticstation.com n]\n**[[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]] and [[Technology Square (Atlanta)|Technology Square]]\n**[[Home Park (Atlanta)|Home Park]] [http://www.homepark.org n]\n**[[Loring Heights (Atlanta)|Loring Heights]]\n**[[Sherwood Forest (Atlanta)|Sherwood Forest]]\n\n====West Midtown / Westside====\n*[[West Midtown]], a.k.a. Westside or The West Side, is an agglomeration of neighborhoods west of I-75/85 (frequently referred to as the \"Connector\") and is an unofficial area whose definition varies, and includes:\n**[[Berkeley Park]]\n**[[Blandtown]]\n** Western [[Home Park (Atlanta)|Home Park]]\n**[[Howell Station|Knight Park/Howell Station]]\n**[[Marietta Street Artery]]\nSometimes Bolton and Hills Park are also included (see below: [[Neighborhoods of Atlanta#Northwestern Atlanta|Northwestern Atlanta]])\n{{col-break}}\n\n{{anchor|East}}\n\n====East Side====\n*[[Atkins Park]]\n*[[Avondale Estates]]\n*[[Cabbagetown (Atlanta)|Cabbagetown]]\n*[[Candler Park]]\n*[[Druid Hills, Georgia|Druid Hills]] (part in Atlanta)\n*[[Decatur, Georgia|Decatur]]\n*[[East Atlanta]]\n*[[East Lake (Atlanta)|East Lake]]\n*[[Edgewood (Atlanta)|Edgewood]]\n*[[Inman Park]]\n*[[Kirkwood (Atlanta)|Kirkwood]]\n*[[Lake Claire (Atlanta)|Lake Claire]]\n*[[Lindridge-Martin Manor|Lindridge&#8209;Martin&nbsp;Manor]]\n*[[Morningside-Lenox Park|Morningside&#8209;Lenox&nbsp;Park]]\n*[[Oakland (Atlanta)|Oakland]]\n*[[Old Fourth Ward]]\n*[[Ormewood Park]]\n*[[Piedmont Heights (Atlanta)|Piedmont Heights]]\n*[[Poncey-Highland]]\n*[[Reynoldstown]]\n*[[Sweet Auburn]]\n*[[Scottdale, Georgia|Scottdale]]\n*[[Virginia-Highland]]\n{{col-break}}\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n{{col-end}}\nThe [[Little Five Points]] district is located where [[Inman Park]] and [[Candler Park]] meet.\n\n===Southeastern Atlanta===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*Amal Heights\n*[[Benteen Park]]\n*Betmar LaVilla\n*Blair Villa/Poole Creek\n*Boulevard Heights\n*Browns Mill Park\n*[[Chosewood Park]]\n*Custer/McDonough/Guice\n*Englewood Manor ([[Atlanta Housing Authority|AHA]] property demolished 2008)\n*Glenrose Heights\n*[[Grant Park (Atlanta)|Grant Park]]\n*[[High Point (Atlanta)|High Point]]\n*[[Joyland (Atlanta)|Joyland]]\n*Lakewood\n*[[Lakewood Heights (Atlanta)|Lakewood Heights]]\n{{col-break}}\n*Leila Valley ([[Atlanta Housing Authority|AHA]] property demolished 2008)\n*Norwood Manor\n*Orchard Knob\n*[[Peoplestown]]\n*Polar Rock\n*Rebel Valley Forest\n*Rosedale Heights\n*[[South Atlanta]]\n*South River Gardens\n*State Facility\n*[[Summerhill (Atlanta)|Summerhill]]\n*Swallow Circle/Baywood\n*[[Atlanta mixed-income communities#The Villages at Carver|The Villages at Carver]]\n*Thomasville Heights\u2014 not to be confused with the [[Demolished public housing projects in Atlanta#Thomasville Heights|former housing project of the same name]], located near the neighborhood. ([[Atlanta Housing Authority|AHA]] property demolished 2010\u201311)\n*Woodland Hills\n{{col-break}}\n[[File:Neighborhoods of Southeast Atlanta.jpg|thumb|350px|right|Neighborhoods of Southeast Atlanta]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Southwestern Atlanta===\n{{See also|SWATS}}\n[[File:Neighborhoods of Southwest Atlanta.jpg|thumb|left|900px|Southwest Atlanta]]\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*Adams Park\n*[[Adamsville (Atlanta)|Adamsville]]\n*Arlington Estates\n*[[Ashley Collegetown]] (former [[Demolished public housing projects in Atlanta#Harris Chiles|Harris Chiles]])\n*[[Atlanta mixed-income communities#Ashley Courts at Cascade|Ashley Courts]]\n*[[Ashview Heights]]\n*[[Atlanta University Center]]\n*Audubon Forest\n*Audubon Forest West\n*Baker Hills\n*Bakers Ferry\n*Beecher Hills\n*[[Ben Hill (Atlanta)|Ben Hill]]\n*Ben Hill Acres\n*Ben Hill Forest\n*Ben Hill Pines\n*Ben Hill Terrace\n*Boulder Park\n*Brentwood\n*Briar Glen\n*Bush Mountain\n*Butner/Tell\n*Campbellton Road\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Capitol View (Atlanta)|Capitol View]]\n*[[Capitol View Manor]]\n*Carroll Heights\n*Cascade Avenue/Road\n*Cascade Green\n*[[Cascade Heights]]\n*Chalet Woods\n*[[Collier Heights]]\n*Deerwood\n*East Ardley Road\n*Elmco Estates\n*Fairburn\n*Fairburn Heights\n*Fairburn Road/Wisteria Lane\n*Fairburn Tell\n*Fairburn Mays\n*Fairway Acres\n*Florida Heights\n*[[Fort McPherson]]\n*Fort Valley\n*Green Acres Valley\n*Green Forest Acres\n*[[Greenbriar (Atlanta)|Greenbriar]]\n*Greenbriar Village\n{{col-break}}\n*Hammond Park\n*Harland Terrace\n*Heritage Valley\n*Horseshoe Community\n*[[Hunter Hills]]\n*Huntington\n*Ivan Hill\n*[[Just Us (Atlanta)|Just Us]]\n*Kings Forest\n*Lake Estates\n*Laurens Valley\n*Magnum Manor\n*Mays\n*Meadowbrook Forest\n*[[Mechanicsville (Atlanta)|Mechanicsville]]\n*Mellwood\n*[[Midwest Cascade]]\n*Mt. Gilead Woods\n*Niskey Cove\n*[[Niskey Lake]]\n*Oakcliff\n*[[Oakland City (Atlanta)|Oakland City]]\n*Old Fairburn Village\n*Old Gordon\n{{col-break}}\n*Pomona Park\n*[[Perkerson (Atlanta)|Perkerson]]\n*Peyton Forest\n*[[Pittsburgh (Atlanta)|Pittsburgh]]\n*Princeton Lakes\n*Regency Trace\n*Ridgecrest Forest\n*Rue Royal\n*Sandlewood Estates\n*South Oaks\n*Southwest\n*[[Summerdale Commons]]\n*[[Sylvan Hills (Atlanta)|Sylvan Hills]]\n*Tampa Park\n*[[Venetian Hills]]\n*[[West End (Atlanta)|West End]]\n*West Manor\n*Westhaven\n*[[Westview (Atlanta)|Westview]]\n*Westwood Terrace\n*Wildwood\n*Wildwood Forest\n*Wilson Mill Meadows\n*Wisteria Gardens\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Northwestern Atlanta===\n[[File:Neighborhoods of Northwest Atlanta.jpg|thumb|left|900px|Northwest Atlanta]]\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*Almond Park\n*Atlanta Industrial Park\n*[[Bankhead (Atlanta)|Bankhead]]\n*[[Bankhead Courts]] ([[Atlanta Housing Authority|AHA]] property demolished 2010)\n*[[Bolton (Atlanta)|Bolton]]\n*Bolton Hills\n*[[Bowen Apartments]]\n{{col-break}}\n*Brookview Heights\n*Carey Park\n*Carver Hills\n*[[Center Hill (Atlanta)|Center Hill]]\n*Chattahoochee\n*[[Dixie Hills, Atlanta|Dixie Hills]]\n*[[English Avenue (Atlanta)|English Avenue]]\n*English Park\n*[[Grove Park (Atlanta)|Grove Park]]\n{{col-break}}\n*Harvel Homes\n*Hills Park\n*[[Hunter Hills]]\n*[[Knight Park-Howell Station|Knight Park/Howell Station]]\n*Monroe Heights(45)\n*[[Mozley Park]]\n*Penelope Neighbors\n*[[Riverside (Atlanta)|Riverside]]\n{{col-break}}\n*Rockdale\n*Scotts Crossing\n*[[Vine City]]\n*[[Washington Park (Atlanta, Georgia)|Washington Park]]\n*[[Atlanta mixed-income communities#West Highlands|West Highlands]] (includes Perry Homes)\n*[[West Lake (MARTA station)|West Lake]]\n*[[Whittier Mill Village]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Buckhead===\n[[File:Neighborhoods of Buckhead.jpg|thumb|left|900px|Buckhead]]\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Ardmore (Atlanta)|Ardmore]]\n*[[Argonne Forest (Atlanta)|Argonne Forest]]\n*Arden/Habersham\n*[[Brookhaven (Atlanta)|Brookhaven]]\n*[[Buckhead Forest]]\n*Brandon\n*[[Brookwood (Atlanta)|Brookwood]]\n*[[Brookwood Hills]]\n*[[Buckhead Forest]]\n*[[Buckhead Village]]\n*Castlewood\n*Channing Valley (also includes Memorial Park)\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Chastain Park]]\n*[[Collier Hills]] (also includes [[Brookwood Hills]])\n*Colonial Homes\n*East Chastain Park\n*[[Garden Hills]]\n*Haynes Manor\n*[[Historic Brookhaven (Atlanta)|Historic Brookhaven]]\n*Kingswood\n*[[Lindbergh/Morosgo]]\n*[[Loring Heights (Atlanta)|Loring Heights]]\n*[[Margaret Mitchell (Atlanta neighborhood)|Margaret Mitchell]]\n*Mount Paran/Northside\n{{col-break}}\n*Mount Paran Parkway\n*[[North Buckhead]]\n*[[Paces (Atlanta)|Paces]]\n*Peachtree Heights East\n*Peachtree Heights West\n*[[Peachtree Hills]]\n*[[Peachtree Park]]\n*[[Pine Hills (Atlanta)|Pine Hills]]\n*Randall Mill\n{{col-break}}\n*Ridgedale Park\n*Springlake\n*South Tuxedo Park\n*[[Tuxedo Park (Atlanta)|Tuxedo Park]]\n*[[Underwood Hills]]\n*West Paces Ferry/Northside\n*Westminister/Milmar\n*West Peachtree Battle (Known as Wesley Battle by city government<ref name=\"atlnpu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atlantaga.gov/index.aspx?page=404|title=Atlanta, GA : NPU by Neighborhood|website=Atlantaga.gov|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref>)\n*Whitewater Creek\n*Wildwood\n*Woodfield\n*Wyngate\n{{col-end}}\n