{"title_page": "2015 World Snooker Championship", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|Snooker tournament, held 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox Individual Snooker Tournament\n| tournament_name    = 2015 Betfred [[World Snooker Championship]]\n| logo               =[[File:World Snooker Championship 2015 Logo.png|230px]]\n| dates              = 18 April \u2013 4 May 2015\n| venue              = [[Crucible Theatre]]\n| location           = [[Sheffield]]\n| country            = [[England]]\n| organisation       = [[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]]\n| format             = [[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]] event\n| Total prize fund   = \u00a31,364,000\n| winners_share      = \u00a3300,000\n| highest_break      = {{flagathlete|[[Stuart Bingham]]|ENG}} (145)<br>{{flagathlete|[[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]]|AUS}} (145)\n| winner             = {{flagathlete|[[Stuart Bingham]]|ENG}}\n| runner_up          = {{flagathlete|[[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]]|ENG}}\n| score              = 18\u201315\n| previous           = [[2014 World Snooker Championship|2014]]\n| next               = [[2016 World Snooker Championship|2016]]\n}}\nThe '''2015 World Snooker Championship''' (also referred to as the '''2015 Betfred World Snooker Championship''' for the purposes of sponsorship) was a professional [[snooker]] tournament, that took place from 18 April to 4 May 2015 at the [[Crucible Theatre]] in [[Sheffield]], England. It was the 39th consecutive year that the [[World Snooker Championship]] had been held at the Crucible and this was the final [[Snooker world rankings|ranking]] event of the [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/2015 season]]. [[Betfred]] sponsored the event for the first time in three years, having previously sponsored the tournament from 2009 to 2012. Qualifying for the event took place between 8 and 15 April 2015 at the [[Ponds Forge International Sports Centre]], Sheffield.\n\n[[Mark Selby]] was the defending champion, having defeated [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the [[2014 World Snooker Championship|2014 final]]. Selby lost 9\u201313 in the second round to event debutant [[Anthony McGill (snooker player)|Anthony McGill]]. Selby fell to the [[Crucible curse]], becoming the 16th first-time champion unable to defend his title at the venue. [[Shaun Murphy]] the [[2005 World Snooker Championship|2005 winner]] met [[Stuart Bingham]] in the final. Bingham, a 50\u20131 outsider at the start of the tournament, defeated Murphy 18\u201315 in the final to win the first world title of his 20-year professional career. At the age of 38, Bingham became the oldest player to win the title since [[Ray Reardon]] in [[1978 World Snooker Championship|1978]].\n\nThe tournament featured a total of 86 [[century break]]s, a record for the championships and higher than 83 centuries set in [[2009 World Snooker Championship|2009]]. The highest break was 145, achieved by both Bingham and [[Neil Robertson]]. The event had a prize fund of [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]1,364,000 with the winner receiving \u00a3300,000.\n\n==Overview==\nThe [[World Snooker Championship]] is an annual [[cue sport]] tournament and the official professional world championship of the game of [[snooker]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Snooker championship |work=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer |date=11 May 1927 |accessdate=12 March 2019 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000687/19270511/425/0020 |via=British Newspaper Archive}}</ref> Founded in the late 19th century by [[British Army]] soldiers stationed in India,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/ |title=Origins of Snooker |first=Peter |last=Clare |year=2008 |work=Billiard & Snooker Heritage Collection |accessdate=8 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103150005/http://snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/ |archivedate=3 January 2017}}</ref> the sport was played in the United Kingdom.<ref>Everton, Clive (1991). ''Snooker and Billiards: Techniques, Tactics and Training (Crowood Sports Guides).'' The Crowood Press. Chapter 1. {{ISBN|978-1-85223-480-5}}</ref> In modern times, however, it has been played worldwide, especially in East and Southeast Asia nations such as China, Hong Kong and Thailand.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Rise Of China \u2013 World Snooker |website=World Snooker |access-date=13 March 2019 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/the-rise-of-china/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419145915/http://www.worldsnooker.com/the-rise-of-china/ |archive-date=19 April 2018 |url-status=live |date=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe world championship sees 32 professional players compete in one-on-one snooker matches in a [[single elimination]] format, each played over several {{cuegloss|frames}}. The event's 32 players are selected through a mix of the world snooker rankings, and a pre-tournament qualification round.<ref>{{cite web |title=2017 Betfred World Snooker Championship \u2013 World Snooker |website=World Snooker |access-date=6 March 2019 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/tournaments/betfred-world-championship-2017/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423051051/http://www.worldsnooker.com/tournaments/betfred-world-championship-2017/ |archive-date=12 July 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Crucible Draw And Format \u2013 World Snooker |website=World Snooker |date=9 April 2019 |access-date=17 April 2019 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/crucible-draw-format/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417192039/http://www.worldsnooker.com/crucible-draw-format/ |archive-date=17 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first world championship in [[1927 World Snooker Championship|1927]] was won by [[Joe Davis]], the final being held in [[Camkin's Hall]], Birmingham, England.<ref>{{cite web |last=Turner |first=Chris |title=World Professional Championship |url=http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/world.html |work=cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk |publisher=Chris Turner's Snooker Archive |accessdate=9 February 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724180133/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/world.html |archivedate=24 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=1927 World Professional Championship |url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/27world.htm |work=globalsnookercentre.co.uk |publisher=Global Snooker Centre |accessdate=29 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041010103752/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/27world.htm |archivedate=10 October 2004}}</ref> Since 1977, the event has been held at the [[Crucible Theatre]] in Sheffield, England.<ref>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1392311|desc=The Crucible Theatre|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref> [[Stephen Hendry]] is the most successful player in the modern era, having won the championship seven times.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Championship \u2013 Roll of Honour |url=http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-tournaments-archive-world-championship-roll-of-honour.asp |website=global-snooker.com |accessdate=18 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222034318/http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-tournaments-archive-world-championship-roll-of-honour.asp |archivedate=22 February 2012}}</ref>{{efn|The \"modern era\" is considered to be after the [[1970-69 snooker season]].<ref name=\"stub_Worl\">{{Cite web |title=World Snooker Championship Tickets \u2013 StubHub UK |author= |work=StubHub |date= |access-date=13 April 2020 |url= https://www.stubhub.co.uk/world-snooker-championship-tickets/grouping/724627/ |quote=}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"trip_BBCS\">{{Cite web |title=BBC Snooker Triple Crown |author= |work=Triple DDD Sports Ltd |date= |access-date=13 April 2020 |url= https://www.tripledddsports.com/blogs/the-best-advice-from-our-in-house-professionals/bbc-snooker-triple-crown |quote=}}</ref>}} England's [[Mark Selby]] won the [[2014 World Snooker Championship|previous year's championship]] by defeating countryman [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the final 18\u201314.<ref>{{cite news |last=Weaver |first=Paul |title=Mark Selby beats Ronnie O'Sullivan 18\u201314 to win world snooker final |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/may/05/mark-selby-ronnie-osullivan-world-snooker-final |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |date=6 May 2014 |accessdate=16 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506043724/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/may/05/mark-selby-ronnie-osullivan-world-snooker-final |archive-date=6 May 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The winner of the 2015 event earned prize money of [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]300,000, from a total pool of \u00a31,364,000.<ref name=Prize/> The event was sponsored by sports betting company [[Betfred]] having previously sponsored the event from 2009 to 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=535 |title=Betfred World Championship Qualifiers |website=snooker.org |accessdate=2 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422211927/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=535 |archivedate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Betfred to sponsor World Championship |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/betfred-to-sponsor-world-championship/ |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |date=13 March 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415050435/http://www.worldsnooker.com/betfred-to-sponsor-world-championship/ |archive-date=15 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Nunns |first=Hector |title=Betfred return as World Championship sponsors |url=http://www.inside-snooker.com/snooker/2015/3/13/betfred-return-as-world-championship-sponsors |publisher=Inside Snooker |date=13 March 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402110012/http://www.inside-snooker.com/snooker/2015/3/13/betfred-return-as-world-championship-sponsors |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Format===\nThe 2015 World Snooker Championship was held between 18&nbsp;April and 4&nbsp;May 2015 in [[Sheffield]], England.<ref>{{cite web |title=Crucible Draw And Format \u2013 World Snooker |website=World Snooker |date=9 April 2019 |access-date=17 April 2019 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/crucible-draw-format/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417192039/http://www.worldsnooker.com/crucible-draw-format/ |archive-date=17 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The tournament was the last of 11&nbsp;rankings events in the [[2014-15 snooker season]] on the [[World Snooker Tour]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=2&season=2014 |title=Tournament Calendar 2014/2015 |publisher=Snooker.org |accessdate=16 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122101140/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=2&season=2014 |archive-date=22 January 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2014/15 Calendar |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/Tournaments/FullCalendar |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |accessdate=1 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317080223/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/Tournaments/FullCalendar |archive-date=17 March 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Calendar 2014/2015 |url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=2&season=2014 |publisher=Snooker.org |accessdate=15 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625091256/http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=2&season=2014 |archive-date=25 June 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> It featured a 32-player main draw that took place at the Crucible Theatre, as well as a 128-player qualifying draw that was played at the 8 and 15 April 2015 at the [[Ponds Forge|Ponds Forge International Sports Centre]], finishing three days before the start of the main draw.<ref>{{cite web |title=Crucible Draw And Format \u2013 World Snooker |website=World Snooker |date=9 April 2019 |access-date=17 April 2019 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/crucible-draw-format/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417192039/http://www.worldsnooker.com/crucible-draw-format/ |archive-date=17 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> This was the 39th consecutive year that the tournament had been held at the Crucible, and it was the 47th successive world championship to be contested through the knockout format after reverting from a challenge match system in the 1960s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Crucible Draw And Format \u2013 World Snooker |website=World Snooker |date=9 April 2019 |access-date=17 April 2019 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/crucible-draw-format/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417192039/http://www.worldsnooker.com/crucible-draw-format/ |archive-date=17 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe top 16 players in the latest world rankings automatically qualified for the main draw as seeded players.<ref name=Official/>{{efn|In the event of the defending champion being ranked outside the top 16, he would replace the player ranked world number 16 as an automatic qualifier.<ref name=Official>{{cite web |title=2015 Betfred World Snooker Championship \u2013 World Snooker |website=World Snooker |access-date=6 March 2019 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/tournaments/betfred-world-championship-2015/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150421101122/http://www.worldsnooker.com/tournaments/betfred-world-championship-2015/ |archive-date=21 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>}} Mark Selby was seeded first overall as the defending champion, while the remaining 15&nbsp;seeds were allocated based on the latest world rankings, released after the penultimate event of the season, the [[2015 China Open (snooker)|China Open]].<ref name=Official/> The number of frames needed to win a match increased with each proceeding round of the main draw, starting with best-of-19-frames matches in the first round, leading up to the final which was played as a best-of-35-frames match.<ref name=Official/><ref>{{cite web |title=Crucible Draw And Format \u2013 World Snooker |website=World Snooker |date=9 April 2019 |access-date=17 April 2019 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/crucible-draw-format/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417192039/http://www.worldsnooker.com/crucible-draw-format/ |archive-date=17 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!--\nAll 16 non-seeded spots in the main draw were filled with players from the qualifying rounds. The qualifying draw consisted of 128&nbsp;players, including 110&nbsp;of the remaining 112&nbsp;players on the World Snooker Tour, as well as 18&nbsp;wildcard places allotted to non-tour players.<ref>{{cite web |title=Criteria set for World Championship invitations |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/criteria-set-world-championship-invitations/ |website=World Snooker |accessdate=17 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318084816/http://www.worldsnooker.com/criteria-set-world-championship-invitations/ |archive-date=18 March 2017 |url-status=live |date=13 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=On Yee, Petrov invited to World Championship |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/yee-petrov-invited-world-championship/ |website=World Snooker |accessdate=29 March 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330013052/http://www.worldsnooker.com/yee-petrov-invited-world-championship/ |archivedate=30 March 2017 |date=28 March 2017}}</ref> These invited players included the [[World Women's Snooker Championship|women's world champion]], the [[EBSA European Under-18 Snooker Championships|European junior champion]], and all four semi-finalists at the [[2018 WSF Championship|amateur championship]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Criteria set for World Championship invitations |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/criteria-set-world-championship-invitations/ |website=World Snooker |accessdate=17 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318084816/http://www.worldsnooker.com/criteria-set-world-championship-invitations/ |archive-date=18 March 2017 |url-status=live |date=13 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=On Yee, Petrov invited to World Championship |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/yee-petrov-invited-world-championship/ |website=World Snooker |accessdate=29 March 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330013052/http://www.worldsnooker.com/yee-petrov-invited-world-championship/ |archivedate=30 March 2017 |date=28 March 2017}}</ref> As with the main draw, half of the participants in the qualifying draw were seeded players; those ranked from 17th to 80th were allocated one of 64&nbsp;seeds in order of their ranking, while the other participants were placed randomly into the draw.<ref>{{cite web |title=On Yee, Petrov invited to World Championship |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/yee-petrov-invited-world-championship/ |website=World Snooker |accessdate=29 March 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330013052/http://www.worldsnooker.com/yee-petrov-invited-world-championship/ |archivedate=30 March 2017 |date=28 March 2017}}</ref> To reach the main draw at the Crucible, players needed to win three best-of-19-frames matches.<ref>{{Cite web |title=World Championship snooker qualifying results 2017 |work=Sporting Life|location=UK |access-date=1 December 2019 |url=https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/world-championship-qualifying/52998 |quote=Players needed to win through three rounds to earn one of the available 16 spots at the Crucible. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907184243/https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/world-championship-qualifying/52998 |archive-date=7 September 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n-->\n\n===Prize fund===\nThe prize fund of the event was raised to \u00a31,364,000 from the previous year's \u00a31,214,000.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kalb |first=Rolf |title=Weltmeisterschaft \u2013 Turnier-Infos zu Weltmeisterschaft |url=https://de.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/weltmeisterschaft-turnier-infos-weltmeisterschaft-082321871--spt.html |publisher=[[Eurosport|Eurosport Deutschland]] |date=10 April 2015 |accessdate=10 April 2015 |language=German |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417152504/https://de.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/weltmeisterschaft-turnier-infos-weltmeisterschaft-082321871--spt.html |archive-date=17 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The breakdown of prize money for this year is shown below:<ref name=Prize>{{cite web |title=Indicative Prize Money Rankings Schedule 2014/2015 Season |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/a5/c1/0,,13165~180645,00.pdf |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |date=12 May 2014 |accessdate=8 April 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517140043/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/a5/c1/0,,13165~180645,00.pdf |archivedate=17 May 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{{div col}}\n*Winner: \u00a3300,000\n*Runner-up: \u00a3125,000\n*Semi-final: \u00a360,000\n*Quarter-final: \u00a330,000\n*Last 16: \u00a320,000\n*Last 32: \u00a312,000\n*Last 48: \u00a39,000\n*Last 80: \u00a36,000\n*Non-televised highest break: \u00a31,000\n*Televised highest break: \u00a310,000\n*Total: \u00a31,364,000\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Participant summary===\nThe event featured 144 partipants, with 128 competing in qualifying alongside 16 invited players.<ref name=\"snoo_Betf\">{{Cite web |title=Betfred World Championship Qualifiers (2015) |last=\u00c5rdalen |first=Hermund |work=snooker.org |access-date=15 March 2020 |url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=368 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408051015/http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=368 |archive-date=8 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> The top 16 seeds automatically qualified for the main draw based on the [[snooker world rankings]] prior to the tournament. Defending champion Mark Selby was seeded 1, while other seeded places were allocated based on the latest [[Snooker world rankings 2014/2015|world rankings]]. The one exception was [[Ali Carter]], who was seeded 13, despite being ranked 31, because his seeding had been frozen while he underwent treatment for cancer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/carter-to-retain-top-16-seeding/ |title=Carter To Retain Top 16 Seeding |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |date=22 October 2014 |accessdate=21 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150616021032/http://www.worldsnooker.com/carter-to-retain-top-16-seeding/ |archive-date=16 June 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> This meant that [[Michael White (snooker player)|Michael White]], ranked 16, had to play in the qualifying tournament. For the first time, players ranked 17\u201332 had to win three qualifying matches, rather than one.<ref name=quali>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/31693252 |title=Reanne Evans: Ladies' champion to face men in world qualifiers |author=Frank Keogh |newspaper=BBC Sport |date=3 March 2015 |access-date=12 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150521093800/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/31693252 |archive-date=21 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"snoo_Does\">{{Cite web |title=Does the World Qualifying Format Help or Hinder the Seeds? |work=SnookerHQ |date=8 April 2015 |access-date=15 March 2020 |url= https://snookerhq.com/2015/04/08/does-the-world-qualifying-format-help-or-hinder-the-seeds/ }}</ref>\n\nTen former world champions competed in the tournament. [[Peter Ebdon]], [[Steve Davis]], and [[Ken Doherty]] lost in the qualifying rounds,<ref>{{cite web |title=World Championship qualifying: Peter Ebdon is knocked out |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32278659 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=12 April 2015 |accessdate=13 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413214412/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32278659 |archive-date=13 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=World Championship: Steve Davis heavily beaten by Kurt Maflin |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32293337 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=13 April 2015 |accessdate=13 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414223727/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32293337 |archive-date=14 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=World Championship: Ken Doherty goes out to Mark Davis |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32324312 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=15 April 2015 |accessdate=15 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416031437/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32324312 |archive-date=16 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> but [[Graeme Dott]] successfully qualified for the main stages.<ref name=\"snoo_Dohe\">{{Cite web |title=Doherty Dumped but Delight for Dott |work=SnookerHQ |date=15 April 2015 |access-date=15 March 2020 |url= https://snookerhq.com/2015/04/15/doherty-dumped-but-delight-for-dott/ }}</ref> Six other former champions ([[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]], [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]], Ronnie O'Sullivan, [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]], Mark Selby, and [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]]) automatically qualified by virtue of their top 16 rankings.<ref name=quali/> Despite losing 1\u201310 to [[Kurt Maflin]], Davis became the first player to compete in a total of 100 World Championship matches, including qualifiers.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hendon |first=Dave |title=30 Years On: Davis wins Black Ball Thriller |url=http://www.inside-snooker.com/snooker/2015/4/12/30-years-on-davis-wins-black-ball-thriller |publisher=Inside Snooker |date=12 April 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418184725/http://www.inside-snooker.com/snooker/2015/4/12/30-years-on-davis-wins-black-ball-thriller |archive-date=18 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Ten-time women's world champion [[Reanne Evans]] attempted to become the first woman to reach the televised stages of the World Championship, but she lost 8\u201310 to Ken Doherty in the first qualifying round.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/10/reanne-evans-crucible-dream-ended-ken-doherty-world-snooker-championship-qualifying |title=Reanne Evans's World dream ended by Ken Doherty in qualifying thriller |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=10 April 2015 |access-date=13 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085025/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/10/reanne-evans-crucible-dream-ended-ken-doherty-world-snooker-championship-qualifying |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Summary==\n===Early rounds===\n[[File:Mark_Selby_at_Snooker_German_Masters_(DerHexer)_2015-02-04_02.jpg|thumb|150px|Defending champion [[Mark Selby]] was eliminated in the second round]]\nFirst-round debutants at the [[Crucible Theatre|Crucible]] were England's [[Craig Steadman]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Hendon |first=Dave |title=Steadman hits dizzy heights |url=http://www.inside-snooker.com/snooker/2015/4/15/steadman-hits-dizzy-heights |publisher=Inside Snooker |date=15 April 2015 |accessdate=16 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416122650/http://www.inside-snooker.com/snooker/2015/4/15/steadman-hits-dizzy-heights |archive-date=16 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Stuart Carrington]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Grimsby cueman Carrington qualifies for World Championships |url=http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Grimsby-cueman-qualifies-World-Championships/story-26340325-detail/story.html |work=[[Grimsby Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Local World]] |location=Grimsby |date=15 April 2015 |accessdate=16 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416121643/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Grimsby-cueman-qualifies-World-Championships/story-26340325-detail/story.html |archive-date=16 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Scotland's [[Anthony McGill (snooker player)|Anthony McGill]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/32491269 |title=World Snooker Championship: McGill can win it, says ex-manager |last=McLeod |first=Rhona |date=27 April 2015 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=13 December 2019}}</ref> and Norway's [[Kurt Maflin]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Snooker: Mark Selby to open World Championship title defence against Norway's Kurt Maflin |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Snooker-Mark-Selby-open-World-Championship-title/story-26343496-detail/story.html |work=[[Leicester Mercury]] |publisher=[[Local World]] |location=Leicester |date=16 April 2015 |accessdate=17 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417112244/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Snooker-Mark-Selby-open-World-Championship-title/story-26343496-detail/story.html |archive-date=17 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> McGill and Carrington had both played at the Crucible before, in the [[Pot Black#Junior Pot Black|Junior Pot Black]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hendon |first=Dave |title=Fab four heading for Crucible |url=http://www.inside-snooker.com/snooker/2015/4/15/fab-four-heading-for-crucible |publisher=Inside Snooker |date=15 April 2015 |accessdate=16 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416122304/http://www.inside-snooker.com/snooker/2015/4/15/fab-four-heading-for-crucible |archive-date=16 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Mark Selby narrowly escaped a first-round exit, recovering from 8\u20139 down against Maflin to clinch a 10\u20139 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mark Selby relies on instinct to survive Crucible scare against Kurt Maflin |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/19/mark-selby-kurt-maflin-snooker-world-championship-sheffield-crucible |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=18 April 2015 |accessdate=29 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505062536/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/19/mark-selby-kurt-maflin-snooker-world-championship-sheffield-crucible |archive-date=5 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> In his match against Steadman, Ronnie O'Sullivan risked a sanction for removing a pair of uncomfortable shoes and playing briefly in his socks, before borrowing a replacement pair of shoes from tournament director Mike Ganley.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/21/ronnie-osullivan-socks-world-championship-snooker |title=Ronnie O'Sullivan plays first-round world championship match in his socks |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 April 2015 |access-date=13 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315180135/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/21/ronnie-osullivan-socks-world-championship-snooker |archive-date=15 March 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Ali Carter, back at the Crucible after extensive treatment for cancer, won his match 10\u20135 against [[Alan McManus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/22/ali-carter-beats-alan-mcmanus-world-snooker-championships-crucible |title=Ali Carter beats Alan McManus on Crucible return following lung cancer |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=22 April 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505055551/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/22/ali-carter-beats-alan-mcmanus-world-snooker-championships-crucible |archive-date=5 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMark Selby succumbed to the [[Crucible curse]] in the second round, losing 9\u201313 to Anthony McGill to become the 16th first-time champion who failed to defend his title since the tournament moved to the Crucible in 1977.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/24/world-championship-anthony-mcgill-mark-selby-shock-win |title=World championship rookie Anthony McGill ends Mark Selby title defence |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=24 April 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150425141115/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/24/world-championship-anthony-mcgill-mark-selby-shock-win |archive-date=25 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Ding Junhui]] defeated John Higgins 13\u20139 to reach only his third quarter-final in nine years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/25/ding-junhui-beats-john-higgins-snooker-world-championship |title=Ding Junhui puts paid to John Higgins' hopes of fifth world championship |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 April 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527141410/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/25/ding-junhui-beats-john-higgins-snooker-world-championship |archive-date=27 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Barry Hawkins]] reached the quarter-finals after defeating [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] 13\u201311, coming back from 8\u201311 behind in the final session.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32461267 |title=World Championship: Barry Hawkins wins Crucible thriller |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=25 April 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427211543/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32461267 |archive-date=27 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Stuart Bingham]] reached his second Crucible quarter-final, winning seven out of the last eight frames to defeat Graeme Dott 13\u20135. Three of the other four-second round matches ended with 13\u20135 wins for Ronnie O'Sullivan over [[Matthew Stevens]], Shaun Murphy over [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]], and Neil Robertson over Ali Carter. Judd Trump defeated Hong Kong's [[Marco Fu]] 13\u20138.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=World Championship 2015 scores and results |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/32267904 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=24 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151203191423/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/32267904 |archive-date=3 December 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Quarter-finals===\nJudd Trump defeated Ding Junhui 13\u20134 to reach his third World Championship semi-final, while Shaun Murphy defeated the last remaining qualifier Anthony McGill 13\u20138 to reach the semi-finals for the first time since 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32508188 |title=World Championship: Judd Trump beats Ding Junhui |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 April 2015 |access-date=12 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924233004/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32508188 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Stuart Bingham reached the first career semi-final with a 13\u20139 victory over tournament favourite Ronnie O'Sullivan, who had beaten Bingham 13\u20134 at the same stage of the tournament two years prior.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32522488 |title=World Championship: Ronnie O'Sullivan stunned by Bingham |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 April 2015 |access-date=12 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029102028/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32522488 |archive-date=29 October 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nA controversial incident occurred in the fifth frame of the match, when O'Sullivan placed his chalk on the table and used it to line up a shot. Referee Terry Camilleri did not penalise O'Sullivan, even though the [[rules of snooker]] call for a seven-point foul if a player uses an object to measure gaps or distances. The referee's handling of the incident was questioned from the commentary box by former world champion Ken Doherty and on [[Twitter]] by former tour referee [[Michaela Tabb]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32502603 |title=World Championship: Ronnie O'Sullivan chalk incident closed |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 April 2015 |access-date=12 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924233003/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32502603 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the last quarter-final match, Barry Hawkins defeated Neil Robertson 13\u201312 to reach the semi-finals for a third consecutive year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32524336 |title=World Snooker Championship: Barry Hawkins beats Neil Robertson 13\u201312 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 April 2015 |access-date=12 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924233007/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32524336 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Hawkins and Robertson produced four century breaks each to equal the record of eight centuries in one match, and set a new record for a 25-frame match at the Crucible.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Quarter-finals |magazine=Snooker Scene |page=20 |publisher=Everton's News Agency |issue=June 2015 <!--This Wikipedia article previously omitted the qualification \"at the Crucible.\" Reliable source for that statement required.-->}}</ref> Their encounter also included the longest frame in the tournament, at 70 minutes and 22 seconds.<ref name=\"BBC Sport\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32508188 |title=World Snooker Championship: Crucible set for all-English semis |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 April 2015 |access-date=12 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924233004/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32508188 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Semi-finals===\nAll four World Championship semi-finalists were English.<ref name=\"BBC Sport\"/> [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]] was the only former champion to reach the last four.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/29/shaun-murphy-world-championship-anthony-mcgill |title=Shaun Murphy reaches Crucible last four by subduing Anthony McGill |date=29 April 2015 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=29 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518083258/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/29/shaun-murphy-world-championship-anthony-mcgill |archive-date=18 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first two sessions between Murphy and Barry Hawkins were one-sided, with Murphy taking a 6\u20132 lead and then extending it to 13\u20133. Even though Hawkins won five out of eight frames in the third session, preventing Murphy from winning the match with a session to spare, Murphy wrapped up a 17\u20139 victory in the final session to reach the third World Championship final of his career.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32563769 |title=World Snooker Championship: Shaun Murphy reaches final |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=2 May 2015 |accessdate=2 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504030237/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32563769 |archive-date=4 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> With five century breaks from Murphy and three from Hawkins, the match again equaled the record for the most centuries in a professional match at the Crucible.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Semi-finals |magazine=Snooker Scene |page=23 |publisher=Everton's News Agency |issue=June 2015}}</ref> In a much closer encounter, Stuart Bingham led Judd Trump 5\u20133 after the first session, 9\u20137 after the second, and 13\u201311 after the third.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/11579791/Stuart-Bingham-reaches-final-with-astonishing-final-frame-thriller.html |title=Stuart Bingham reaches final with astonishing final-frame thriller |date=3 May 2015 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=19 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150521202514/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/11579791/Stuart-Bingham-reaches-final-with-astonishing-final-frame-thriller.html |archive-date=21 May 2015 |url-status=live|last1=Johson |first1=Daniel }}</ref>\t\nFrom 14\u201316 down, Trump produced two consecutive century breaks to force a deciding frame, but Bingham prevailed in the decider to defeat Trump 17\u201316 and reach his first World Championship final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32563769 |title=World Snooker Championship: Stuart Bingham reaches final |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=2 May 2015 |accessdate=2 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504030237/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32563769 |archive-date=4 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Final===\n[[File:Stuart_Bingham_and_Jan_Scheers_at_Snooker_German_Masters_(DerHexer)_2015-02-05_04.jpg|thumb|[[Stuart Bingham]] won the final]]\nAt the age of 38, Stuart Bingham was the oldest first-time finalist at the Crucible since 45-year-old [[Ray Reardon]] in [[1978 World Snooker Championship|1978]], although Reardon had already won five world titles at other venues by that point in his career.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/may/02/stuart-bingham-judd-trump-crucible-world-championship-shaun-murphy |title=Stuart Bingham stakes all on plant to foil Judd Trump 17\u201316 at Crucible |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2 May 2015 |accessdate=2 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504211553/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/may/02/stuart-bingham-judd-trump-crucible-world-championship-shaun-murphy |archive-date=4 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> It was the third appearance in the final for Shaun Murphy, who won the title in [[2005 World Snooker Championship|2005]] with an 18\u201316 victory over Matthew Stevens and was runner-up in [[2009 World Snooker Championship|2009]] when he lost 9\u201318 to John Higgins.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/snooker/story/_/id/12806507/stuart-bingham-shocks-judd-trump-deciding-frame-thriller-set-world-championship-final-shaun-murphy-crucible |title=Stuart Bingham shocks Judd Trump to set up Crucible final with Shaun Murphy |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=2 May 2015 |accessdate=2 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505003223/http://www.espn.co.uk/snooker/story/_/id/12806507/stuart-bingham-shocks-judd-trump-deciding-frame-thriller-set-world-championship-final-shaun-murphy-crucible |archive-date=5 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc._Worl\">{{Cite web |title=World Snooker Championship final as it happened |author= |work=BBC Sport |date= |access-date=15 March 2020 |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/snooker/32102412 |quote=}}</ref> The final was refereed for the first time by Olivier Marteel, from [[Koksijde]] in [[West Flanders]], [[Belgium]]. He was the first Belgian to take charge of a World Championship final, and the second referee from continental Europe to do so, after [[Jan Verhaas]].<ref name=\"Final ref\"/>\n\nIn the opening session of the final, Murphy took a 3\u20130 lead, but Bingham fought back to end the session all-square at 4\u20134. In the second session of nine frames, Murphy began strongly, winning four consecutive frames to move 8\u20134 ahead, but Bingham won four of the next five to reduce Murphy's lead to 9\u20138 overnight.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32576888 |title=World Snooker Championship: Shaun Murphy leads Stuart Bingham |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=3 May 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150506001336/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32576888 |archive-date=6 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Bingham's break of 123 in the 14th frame was the 84th century break compiled at the Crucible in 2015, breaking the previous record of 83 centuries set in 2009.<ref name=\"NewCenturyRecord\">{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/others/snooker-world-championship-final-shaun-murphy-and-stuart-bingham-top-century-mark-10223208.html |title=Snooker World Championship final: Shaun Murphy and Stuart Bingham top century mark |work=[[The Independent]] |date=3 May 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505020955/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/others/snooker-world-championship-final-shaun-murphy-and-stuart-bingham-top-century-mark-10223208.html |archive-date=5 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the third session, Bingham won six of the eight frames to move into a 14\u201311 lead. In the 20th frame, Bingham came close to a [[maximum break]], potting 14 reds and 14 blacks before missing the final red.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32584278 |title=World Snooker Championship: Bingham leads Murphy at Crucible |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=4 May 2015 |accessdate=4 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150506202335/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32584278 |archive-date=6 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Although Murphy won four of the first five frames in the final session to draw level at 15\u201315, Bingham won the 64-minute 31st frame to go 16\u201315 in front, and then added two more frames for an 18\u201315 victory and his first world title.<ref>{{cite news |title=England's Bingham wins maiden world title |url=https://news.yahoo.com/englands-stuart-bingham-wins-world-championship-final-220641308.html |publisher=Yahoo News |date=4 May 2014 |accessdate=4 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505021138/http://news.yahoo.com/englands-stuart-bingham-wins-world-championship-final-220641308.html |archive-date=5 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nBingham had odds of 50\u20131 to win the event prior to the tournament.<ref name=\"BinghamVictory\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32584278 |title=World Snooker Championship: Bingham beats Murphy 18\u201315 |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |work=BBC Sport |date=4 May 2015 |accessdate=10 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150506202335/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32584278 |archive-date=6 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> The achievement made him the oldest player to win the title since [[Ray Reardon]] in 1978. He was the third oldest winner in Crucible history after [[Ray Reardon]] who was 45 in 1978 and [[John Spencer (snooker player)|John Spencer]] who was 41 in 1977.{{efn|[[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] would win the title at 43 in [[2018 World Snooker Championship|2018]].}}<ref name=\"Reardon1978\" /> Winning the title also took him to a career high of second in the [[Snooker world ranking points 2014/2015|world rankings]].<ref name=\"BinghamVictory\" /> The final was noted for its high standard of break-building, with six century breaks and 24 more breaks over 50 in the 33 frames played.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bingham on Top of the World |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/bingham-on-top-of-the-world/ |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |date=5 May 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150507180239/http://www.worldsnooker.com/bingham-on-top-of-the-world/ |archive-date=7 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Main draw==\nShown below are the results for each round. Numbers in brackets denote players seedings, whilst players in bold denote match winners.<ref name=\"WPBSA draw\">{{cite web |title=World Championship 2015 Draw |url=http://3a43ed9bbf8e4c3a0092-e5ae3e47d460213726cd286f2f322a12.r38.cf3.rackcdn.com/e93ca439-6579-4a58-9ffd-99459c993be9.pdf |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |date=16 April 2015 |accessdate=16 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416151503/http://3a43ed9bbf8e4c3a0092-e5ae3e47d460213726cd286f2f322a12.r38.cf3.rackcdn.com/e93ca439-6579-4a58-9ffd-99459c993be9.pdf |archive-date=16 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Betfred World Snooker Championship 2015 Format |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/tournaments/betfred-world-championship-2015/format/ |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |accessdate=7 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415051408/http://www.worldsnooker.com/tournaments/betfred-world-championship-2015/format/ |archive-date=15 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Snooker.org\">{{cite web |title=Betfred World Championship (2015) |url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=367 |publisher=Snooker.org |accessdate=4 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150325155156/http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=367 |archive-date=25 March 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> The draw for the first round took place at Hallamshire Golf Club on 16 April 2015, one day after the end of the last qualifying round.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Paul Hunter Foundation Celebrity Golf Day 2015 |url=http://www.hallamshiregolfclub.co.uk/news/ |publisher=Hallamshire Golf Club |date=27 February 2015 |accessdate=15 April 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415053049/http://www.hallamshiregolfclub.co.uk/news/ |archivedate=15 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32289287 |title=World Snooker Championship: Mark Selby plays Kurt Maflin |date=16 April 2015 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=16 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417062956/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/32289287 |archive-date=17 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\t\n{{World Snooker Championship Rounds\n<!--Date-Place/Player 1/Score 1/Player 2/Score 2 -->\n<!-- LAST 32 -->\n<!--Match1 -->\n|18 April|{{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Mark Selby]] (1)'''|'''10'''|{{flagicon|NOR}} [[Kurt Maflin]]|9\n<!--Match2 -->\n|18 & 19 April|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Stephen Maguire]] (16)|9|{{flagicon|SCO}} '''[[Anthony McGill (snooker player)|Anthony McGill]]'''|'''10'''\n<!--Match3 -->\n|22 April|{{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Joe Perry (snooker playe