} '''[[Robin Hull]]''' || align=\"center\"| '''10'''\u20134 || {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Igor Figueiredo]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Yu Delu]] || align=\"center\"| {{nowrap| 7\u2013'''10'''}} || {{flagicon|SCO}} '''[[Graeme Dott]]'''\n|}\n{{col-2|scale=8px}}\n{|class=\"wikitable \"\n|-\n!width=200|Player\n!width=60|Score\n!width=200|Player\n|-\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]]''' || align=\"center\"| '''10'''\u20133 || {{flagicon|IRL}} [[Ken Doherty]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|WAL}} '''[[Matthew Stevens]]''' || align=\"center\"| '''10'''\u20135 || {{flagicon|NIR}} [[Joe Swail]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|IRL}} [[Fergal O'Brien]] || align=\"center\"| 9\u2013'''10''' || {{flagicon|NOR}} '''[[Kurt Maflin]]'''\n|-\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} '''[[Zhang Anda]]''' || align=\"center\"| '''10'''\u20139 || {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Liang Wenbo]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Xiao Guodong]] || align=\"center\"| 9\u2013'''10''' || {{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Jimmy Robertson (snooker player)|Jimmy Robertson]]'''\n|-\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Robbie Williams (snooker player)|Robbie Williams]]''' || align=\"center\"| '''10'''\u20135 || {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Michael Holt (snooker player)|Michael Holt]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Matthew Selt]]''' || align=\"center\"| '''10'''\u20138 || {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Tom Ford (snooker player)|Tom Ford]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Andrew Higginson]] || align=\"center\"| 9\u2013'''10''' || {{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Robert Milkins]]'''\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Century breaks==\n\n===Televised stage centuries===\nThere were 86 [[century break]]s in the televised stage of the World Championship.<ref name=\"MostCrucibleCenturies\">{{cite web |title=World Championship: century breaks |url=http://livescores.worldsnookerdata.com/Centuries/CenturyBreaks/13820/world-championship |work=worldsnookerdata.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |accessdate=22 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150425002254/http://livescores.worldsnookerdata.com/Centuries/CenturyBreaks/13820/world-championship |archive-date=25 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> This was the highest in World Championship history, ahead of the 83 scored in [[2009 World Snooker Championship#Televised stage centuries|2009]].<ref name=\"BBCSTATS\" /><ref name=\"NewCenturyRecord\" /> For every century break made during the 17-day championship in Sheffield, the title sponsor, [[Betfred]], was due to donate [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]200 to World Snooker's official charity, the [[Bluebell Wood Children's Hospice]]. However, in line with the sponsor's declaration, the donation was rounded up to \u00a325,000 as at least 70 centuries were achieved.<ref>{{cite web |title=Betfred to donate to Bluebell Wood |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/betfred-to-donate-to-bluebell-wood/ |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |date=17 April 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418093722/http://www.worldsnooker.com/betfred-to-donate-to-bluebell-wood/ |archive-date=18 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Neil Robertson and Stuart Bingham made the highest break of the tournament, both making a 145.<ref name=\"BBCSTATS\" />\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* 145, 143, 142, 141, 133, 130, 129, 119, 115, 115, 109 [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]]\n* 145, 123, 112, 106, 105, 104, 102, 102, 102, 100 [[Stuart Bingham]]\n* 139, 118, 116, 110, 104, 103, 100 [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]\n* 138, 127, 125, 121, 121, 121, 111, 106, 106, 105, 105, 101, 100 [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]]\n* 137, 125, 122 [[Anthony McGill (snooker player)|Anthony McGill]]\n* 135, 109 [[Ding Junhui]]\n* 135, 104 [[Ricky Walden]]\n* 133, 129, 127, 113, 111, 111, 109, 108, 108, 102 [[Judd Trump]]\n* 132 [[Zhang Anda]]\n* 131, 109, 108, 108, 108, 104, 104, 103, 103, 102 [[Barry Hawkins]]\n{{col-2}}\n* 131 [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]]\n* 127 [[Ali Carter]]\n* 124, 120, 108, 101 [[Mark Selby]]\n* 120 [[Marco Fu]]\n* 115, 111 [[Matthew Stevens]]\n* 115, 109, 101 [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]]\n* 109, 102 [[Matthew Selt]]\n* 106 [[Jimmy Robertson (snooker player)|Jimmy Robertson]]\n* 106 [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]]\n* 106 [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Qualifying stage centuries===\nThere were 83 century breaks in the qualifying stage of the World Championship:<ref>{{cite web |title=World Championship qualifiers: century breaks |url=http://livescores.worldsnookerdata.com/CenturyBreakList/Tournament/13833 |work=worldsnookerdata.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |accessdate=8 April 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412002431/http://livescores.worldsnookerdata.com/CenturyBreakList/Tournament/13833 |archivedate=12 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Three players, Tom Ford, Craig Steadman and David Morris each made the highest break of qualifying, 140.\n{{div col}}\n* 140, 136, 123, 104 [[Tom Ford (snooker player)|Tom Ford]]\n* 140, 116 [[Craig Steadman]]\n* 140 [[David Morris (snooker player)|David Morris]]\n* 139, 138, 126, 125, 112 [[Robin Hull]]\n* 139, 114 [[Graeme Dott]]\n* 137, 134, 132 [[Zhang Anda]]\n* 135 [[Tony Drago]]\n* 134, 134 [[Andrew Higginson]]\n* 134, 109 [[Sam Baird]]\n* 134 [[Scott Donaldson]]\n* 133, 100 [[Yu Delu]]\n* 132, 111 [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]]\n* 131, 123 [[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh]]\n* 131, 106 [[Mark King (snooker player)|Mark King]]\n* 131 [[Xiao Guodong]]\n* 130, 123 [[David Gilbert (snooker player)|David Gilbert]]\n* 129, 120 [[Dechawat Poomjaeng]]\n* 129 [[Ben Woollaston]]\n* 127 [[Anthony McGill (snooker player)|Anthony McGill]]\n* 125, 110, 106, 102 [[Fergal O'Brien]]\n* 122, 108, 100 [[Kurt Maflin]]\n* 122 [[Tian Pengfei]]\n* 122 [[Jamie Jones (snooker player)|Jamie Jones]]\n* 120, 118 [[Adam Duffy]]\n* 120, 110 [[Jack Lisowski]]\n* 117 [[Igor Figueiredo]]\n* 116 [[Michael White (snooker player)|Michael White]]\n* 116 [[Jamie Burnett]]\n* 115, 113, 110, 103 [[Liang Wenbo]]\n* 115 [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]]\n* 115 [[Liam Highfield]]\n* 113, 100 [[Rod Lawler]]\n* 113 [[Li Hang (snooker player)|Li Hang]]\n* 113 [[Joe Swail]]\n* 111, 103 [[Jimmy Robertson (snooker player)|Jimmy Robertson]]\n* 110 [[Alan McManus]]\n* 108 [[Zhou Yuelong]]\n* 108 [[Noppon Saengkham]]\n* 107 [[Chris Wakelin]]\n* 106 [[Peter Lines]]\n* 106 [[Jimmy White]]\n* 105, 104 [[Robert Milkins]]\n* 105 [[Ashley Carty]]\n* 105 [[Stuart Carrington]]\n* 101 [[Michael Leslie]]\n* 101 [[Michael Holt (snooker player)|Michael Holt]]\n* 101 [[Matthew Selt]]\n* 101 [[Robbie Williams (snooker player)|Robbie Williams]]\n* 100 [[Thanawat Thirapongpaiboon]]\n* 100 [[Luca Brecel]]\n* 100 [[Darryl Hill (snooker player)|Darryl Hill]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{noteslist}}\n{{Reflist|refs=<ref name=\"BBCSTATS\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=World Snooker Championship 2019: Frame scores, stats and full results |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/47696353 |work=BBC Sport |date=6 May 2019 |access-date=24 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915082757/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/47696353 |archive-date=15 September 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Reardon1978\">{{cite news |title=Bingham beats Murphy in dramatic Crucible final |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/snooker/story/_/id/12820453/stuart-bingham-beats-shaun-murphy-18-15-dramatic-world-championship-final-crucible |publisher=ESPN |date=4 May 2014 |accessdate=4 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505003853/http://www.espn.co.uk/snooker/story/_/id/12820453/stuart-bingham-beats-shaun-murphy-18-15-dramatic-world-championship-final-crucible |archive-date=5 May 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|www.worldsnooker.com/page/WorldChampionshipEvent}}\n\n{{World Snooker Championship}}\n{{Snooker season 2014/2015}}\n{{World championships in 2015}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World Snooker Championship, 2015}}\n[[Category:World Snooker Championships|2015]]\n[[Category:2015 in snooker|World Championship]]\n[[Category:2015 in English sport]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Sheffield]]\n[[Category:April 2015 sports events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:May 2015 sports events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Lee Vilenski", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_World_Snooker_Championship"}
{"title_page": "Anthony Crank", "text_new": "'''Anthony Crank''' is an English television presenter, journalist and actor, probably best known for his work on [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[T4 (Channel 4)|T4]]'', [[MTV]] and [[Bingo Night Live]] on [[ITV1]].\n\n==Career==\nCrank was trained in drama at the [[Oldham Theatre Workshop]].<ref name=MEN1/>  He moved to London aged 23 and found work writing for magazines, ultimately becoming celebrity editor for ''[[OK!]]''.<ref name=MEN1>{{cite web |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/food_and_drink/s/1053730_table_talk_anthony_crank |title=Table Talk: Anthony Crank |accessdate=2008-09-26 |author=Dianne Bourne \n |date=2008-06-12 |work=Manchester Evening News| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080830065831/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/food_and_drink/s/1053730_table_talk_anthony_crank| archivedate= 30 August 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>  He has also written for ''[[Miss (magazine)|Miss]]'' and ''[[More (magazine)|More]]'' and regularly contributes to''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]''.\n\nCrank was headhunted for Channel 4 youth strand T4<ref name=MEN1/> for 4 years and has also presented on [[MTV]].  He is one of several presenters on [[BBC]] ''[[Holiday (TV series)|Holiday]]'', Holiday Hit Squad and Departure Lounge and hosted a range of shows for the [[Eat Cinema]] channel as well as working as the main presenter on [[ITV Network|ITV]]'s ''[[Bingo Night Live]]''.  He also works for [[BBC Radio Manchester]] as a regular cover presenter.\n\nCrank has returned to Manchester in order to pursue an acting career.<ref name=MEN1/>  He has been cast as Bill, a policeman in the sixth series of [[Shameless (UK TV series)|Shameless]].<ref name=MEN2>{{cite web |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/showbiz/s/1065187_diary_crank_is_smooth_operator |title=Diary: Crank is smooth operator |accessdate=2008-09-26 |author=Dianne Bourne \n |date=2008-09-03 |work=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> and made his theatre debut in Chris Hoyle's critically acclaimed play, 'The Newspaper Boy', opposite [[Suranne Jones]] and [[Joan Kempson]]. He recently took on the role of bad boy Levi in [[Hollyoaks]] E4 spin-off 'The Morning After The Night Before, and is soon to be seen as one of the central roles as debt collector 'Jimmy' in Simon Powell's Salford based feature film 'Poor, Wee Me', opposite [[Paul Hurstfield]], [[Michelle Holmes]], [[Tim Booth]], [[Ian Mercer]] and [[Suranne Jones]]. He then featured in Hollyoaks again in 2010 as Steve, an arrogant TV Producer making a 'T4' style documentary with the characters Duncan and Theresa. He has also just played a small role as a policeman in Jimmy McGovern's new BBC drama, The Accused.\n\nAnthony has recently worked with acclaimed director Trevor MacFarlane on JB Shorts 3, playing the role of a smarmy politician in \"Backlash\", a spoof party political broadcast written by  James Quinn (Early Doors, Fat Friends). The piece received much critical acclaim for the direction and performances in the Guardian, City Life, Whats On Stage to name just a few.\n\n==Personal life==\nAnthony Crank is gay and supports various gay rights charities and movements, including [[The Albert Kennedy Trust]]; he also supports various Aspergers Syndrome charities. He hosts the mainstage Alternative Music Stage for [[Manchester Pride]] festival each year and is currently a student at the [[Manchester School Of Acting]] under the tuition of Mark Hudson<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ygm.org.uk/home/comingout/celebscomingout/ |title=Celebs Coming Out |accessdate=2008-09-26 |date= |work=Young Gay Men |publisher=[[Terrence Higgins Trust]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stonewall.org.uk/media/current_releases/1937.asp |archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20080410095510/http://www.stonewall.org.uk/media/current_releases/1937.asp |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-04-10 |title=Second Stonewall Awards ceremony 2007 |accessdate=2008-09-26 |publisher=[[Stonewall (UK)]] }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\nhttps://web.archive.org/web/20090218054746/http://www.whatsonstage.com/blogs/manchester/2009/02/10/review-the-newspaper-boy/\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eatcinema.com Eat Cinema website]\n*[http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/t4/stars/presenters/antcrank.html mini bio at channel 4]\n*[http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/t4/interview/cranky_diary.html T4 Interview with Crank]\n*[http://www.manchesterschoolofacting.co.uk/manchesterschooe.html Manchester School Of Acting]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crank, Anthony}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British television presenters]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT broadcasters from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''Anthony Crank''' is an English television presenter, journalist and actor, probably best known for his work on [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[T4 (Channel 4)|T4]]'', [[MTV]] and [[Bingo Night Live]] on [[ITV1]].\n\n==Career==\nCrank was trained in drama at the [[Oldham Theatre Workshop]].<ref name=MEN1/>  He moved to London aged 23 and found work writing for magazines, ultimately becoming celebrity editor for ''[[OK!]]''.<ref name=MEN1>{{cite web |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/food_and_drink/s/1053730_table_talk_anthony_crank |title=Table Talk: Anthony Crank |accessdate=2008-09-26 |author=Dianne Bourne \n |date=2008-06-12 |work=Manchester Evening News| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080830065831/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/food_and_drink/s/1053730_table_talk_anthony_crank| archivedate= 30 August 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>  He has also written for ''[[Miss (magazine)|Miss]]'' and ''[[More (magazine)|More]]'' and regularly contributes to''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]''.\n\nCrank was headh